# Roadmap

Project Why Not Us is not a short-term project, nor is it intended to produce a single document.

It is an ongoing effort to collaboratively build an evidence-based, transparent and community-driven framework for the long-term development of Indian football.

Like the National Football Development Code itself, this roadmap is a living document and will continue to evolve as the project grows.

---

# Phase I — The Question

**Current Status:** 🟢 In Progress

Every movement begins with a question.

For Project Why Not Us, that question is simple.

**Why not us?**

The objective of this phase is to introduce the idea behind the National Football Development Code, build awareness and establish a community willing to participate in its development.

### Objectives

* Publish the Public Discussion Draft.
* Release Version 0.1 of the National Football Development Code.
* Establish the GitHub repository and collaboration platform.
* Develop the initial project governance framework.
* Invite contributions from players, coaches, referees, researchers, journalists, lawyers, administrators and supporters.
* Build an initial collection of research papers, regulations and statistical resources.

### Success Indicators

* Active GitHub repository.
* Community discussions initiated.
* First external contributors.
* Public feedback received.
* Initial media and stakeholder engagement.

---

# Phase II — The Conversation

**Status:** Planned

No proposal is perfect.

The purpose of this phase is to transform the NFDC from an individual initiative into a community conversation.

Constructive criticism is encouraged.

Better ideas are welcomed.

Every proposal is open to discussion.

### Objectives

* Review public feedback.
* Expand research and comparative studies.
* Improve citations and supporting evidence.
* Invite subject matter experts to review draft chapters.
* Publish revised editions based on community input.
* Create structured discussion forums for major policy areas.

### Success Indicators

* Increased contributor participation.
* Peer-reviewed proposals.
* Improved documentation.
* Growing repository of evidence and references.

---

# Phase III — The Community

**Status:** Planned

Indian football cannot be understood from a single perspective.

This phase focuses on bringing together people from different backgrounds to collaboratively improve the project.

The goal is not merely to grow the repository.

The goal is to grow the community behind it.

### Objectives

* Establish editorial and review workflows.
* Create working groups for specialised subjects.
* Encourage state-specific and regional research.
* Publish regular progress reports.
* Develop contributor onboarding resources.
* Release Version 0.5 of the NFDC.

### Working Groups (Illustrative)

* Governance
* Grassroots Football
* School & University Football
* Women's Football
* Coaching & Refereeing
* Sports Science
* Infrastructure
* Finance
* International Pathways
* Football Law & Regulations
* Data & Statistics

### Success Indicators

* Active working groups.
* Regular community meetings.
* Contributions from multiple disciplines.
* Transparent editorial process.

---

# Phase IV — The Framework

**Status:** Planned

By this stage, the NFDC should no longer resemble a collection of ideas.

It should become a structured policy framework.

The emphasis shifts from identifying problems to proposing implementable solutions.

### Objectives

* Complete all major chapters of the NFDC.
* Draft model policies and model regulations.
* Develop implementation frameworks.
* Establish measurable performance indicators.
* Create monitoring and evaluation mechanisms.
* Publish Version 1.0.

### Success Indicators

* Complete technical draft.
* Expert-reviewed recommendations.
* Publicly documented revision history.
* Community consensus on core principles.

---

# Phase V — From Framework to Impact

**Status:** Long-Term Vision

The publication of Version 1.0 is not the end of this journey.

It is the beginning.

The long-term ambition of Project Why Not Us is to become a trusted community platform for evidence-based football policy, research and public engagement.

Potential future initiatives include:

* Annual State of Indian Football Reports.
* Open football statistics and datasets.
* Policy briefs on emerging issues.
* State Football Development Frameworks.
* Educational resources.
* Research fellowships.
* Public consultations.
* Partnerships with academic institutions, clubs and governing bodies.

Success will not be measured by downloads or social media impressions.

It will be measured by meaningful conversations, stronger research, better policies and, ultimately, a stronger future for Indian football.

---

# Guiding Principle

The National Football Development Code was never intended to be written by one person.

It is intended to be improved by everyone willing to ask difficult questions, challenge assumptions and work towards better answers.

This roadmap is therefore not a promise.

It is an invitation.
